excerpt: Family-friendly mini-zoo offering a collection of live tropical insects from around the world.
detail_description: Victoria Bug Zoo is a family-friendly mini-zoo located at 631 Courtney St in Victoria. It offers a unique collection of live tropical insects from around the world, providing an up-close experience with the beauty and curiosity of these creatures. The zoo is open daily from 10:00 AM to 5:00 PM, making it an accessible and educational attraction for visitors of all ages. If you're looking for fun activities in Victoria, this mini-zoo is definitely worth a visit!
name: Victoria Bug Zoo
address: 631 Courtney St, Victoria, BC V8W 1B8, Canada

excerpt: This museum showcases natural wonders like dinosaurs & includes an IMAX movie theatre.
detail_description: The Royal BC Museum is a must-visit destination showcasing natural wonders like dinosaurs and featuring an IMAX movie theatre. The region offers various attractions such as Craigdarroch Castle, Cathedral Grove, Pacific Rim National Park Reserve, Rathtrevor Beach Provincial Park, and Mount Washington Alpine Resort. Visitors can also enjoy activities like the Victoria Panorama Seaplane Tour, Butchart Gardens visit, whale watching adventure from Victoria, and more.
name: Royal BC Museum
address: 675 Belleville St., Victoria, BC V8W 9W2, Canada

excerpt: Bustling destination with recreational cruises, summer festivals, ferries & whale watching jaunts.
detail_description: The Inner Harbour Pathway in Victoria is a bustling hub of activity, offering recreational cruises, summer festivals, ferries, and whale-watching tours. It serves as the oldest part of the city and is surrounded by iconic landmarks such as the BC Parliament Buildings and the Fairmont Empress Hotel. During spring and summer, it becomes a lively waterfront promenade with street food vendors, live entertainment acts, musicians, artists, and more.
name: Inner-Harbour Pathway
address: Victoria, BC V8W 3M6, Canada

excerpt: Ornate Victorian castle built by the coal baron Robert Dunsmuir between 1887 & 1890, open for tours.
detail_description: Craigdarroch Castle is a grand Victorian mansion constructed by coal baron Robert Dunsmuir in the late 19th century. It's open for tours and is one of the notable attractions in Victoria, British Columbia. The region offers a variety of activities including visits to the Royal BC Museum, Cathedral Grove, Pacific Rim National Park Reserve, Rathtrevor Beach Provincial Park, and Mount Washington Alpine Resort. Additionally, visitors can enjoy sightseeing tours, whale watching adventures, and wine tours.
name: Craigdarroch Castle
address: 1050 Joan Crescent, Victoria, BC V8S 3L5, Canada

detail_description: Beacon Hill Park is a sprawling 200-acre urban oasis nestled in Victoria. The park boasts an intricate network of walking paths that meander past serene ponds, elegant fountains, and majestic towering trees. Visitors can also spot an array of wildlife such as peacocks and herons while strolling through the lush gardens.
name: Beacon Hill Park
address: Victoria, BC V8W 9J4, Canada

excerpt: This Chinese neighbourhood, Canada's oldest, has restaurants, shops & colourful architecture.
detail_description: Victoria’s Chinatown National Historic Site is Canada's oldest Chinese neighborhood, featuring a vibrant mix of restaurants, shops, and colorful architecture. It offers a unique cultural experience with its rich history and lively atmosphere. Visitors can explore the area's local cuisine, charming boutiques, and immerse themselves in the dynamic energy of this historic site. Whether it's indulging in delicious food or admiring the distinctive architectural charm, a visit to Victoria’s Chinatown promises an enriching and enjoyable experience for all.
name: Victoria’s Chinatown National Historic Site
address: 500 Fisgard St, Victoria, BC V8W 1R4, Canada

excerpt: Miniature-themed dioramas & displays representing historical times & fictional worlds.
detail_description: Miniature World, located near the Fairmont Empress hotel in Victoria, offers over 80 detailed displays of historical and fictional scenes. Visitors can immerse themselves in miniature dioramas accompanied by appropriate sounds, bringing these worlds to life. The attraction features the world's smallest operational sawmill, two of the largest dollhouses, and one of the longest model railways. With themes like Circus World, Frontierland, Space 2201, Fantasyland, and King Arthur's Camelot among others.
name: Miniature World
address: 649 Humboldt St, Victoria, BC V8W 1A7, Canada

excerpt: Outdoor collection of replica totem poles & historic buildings including a convent & carving studio.
detail_description: Thunderbird Park is a cultural oasis adjacent to the Royal BC Museum in Victoria, offering a serene and educational experience. The park features a stunning collection of Indigenous totem poles, including replicas of original totems from the First Peoples Gallery inside the museum. Visitors can explore historic buildings such as a convent and carving studio, as well as the iconic Mungo Martin House, named after a renowned local carver.
name: Thunderbird Park
address: 638 Douglas St, Victoria, BC V8V 2P8, Canada

excerpt: Sloping 1.4-acre garden, begun in 1946, with rhododendrons, native rocks, ponds & a teahouse.
detail_description: Nestled in a 1.4-acre space, Abkhazi Garden is a captivating retreat established in 1946 by Prince and Princess Abkhazi. This enchanting garden boasts vibrant rhododendrons, native rocks, tranquil ponds, and a charming teahouse. It serves as a testament to the couple's love story and their dedication to horticulture.
name: Abkhazi Garden
address: 1964 Fairfield Rd, Victoria, BC V8S 1H2, Canada

excerpt: Formerly a gambling district, this narrow, brick-lined alley now houses boutiques & art galleries.
detail_description: Fan Tan Alley, located in Victoria's oldest Chinatown, is a charming narrow street lined with red-brick heritage buildings that now house various boutiques, art galleries, tea shops, and ice cream parlors. It offers a unique shopping experience with its diverse range of products including skincare items, trendy clothing, vintage vinyl records, and Asian-inspired snacks. The alleyway is also home to the Gates of Harmonious Interest and provides a glimpse into the history of old China.
name: Fan Tan Alley
address: Victoria, BC, Canada

excerpt: Regal place at Fairmont Empress Hotel with locally sourced special-occasion entrees & global wines.
detail_description: Nestled within the historic Fairmont Empress Hotel, Q at the Fairmont Empress is a luxurious destination that perfectly marries modern sophistication with Victorian elegance. This upscale lounge invites guests to indulge in a diverse selection of globally inspired wines and expertly crafted cocktails, all curated by talented mixologists. After a day of exploring Victoria's charming downtown or soaking in breathtaking views of the Inner Harbour, unwind at Q where you can savor exquisite libations amidst an atmosphere steeped in timeless grandeur.
name: Q AT THE FAIRMONT EMPRESS
address: 721 Government St, Victoria, BC V8W 1W5, Canada

excerpt: Elegant 74-hectare Victorian park with trees & landscaped gardens, ponds, peacocks & a bandshell.
detail_description: Beacon Hill Park is a charming 74-hectare Victorian park in Victoria, B.C. It features beautifully landscaped gardens, ponds, and majestic trees. Visitors can enjoy the sight of peacocks roaming freely and relax by the bandshell. The park offers a serene escape for nature lovers and provides a picturesque setting for leisurely strolls or picnics. With its tranquil ambiance and natural beauty, Beacon Hill Park is a must-visit destination in Victoria.
name: Beacon Hill Park
address: 100 Cook St, Victoria, BC V8V 4Z8, Canada

excerpt: Landmark 20th-century Anglican cathedral featuring a Gothic facade, a pipe organ & a labyrinth.
detail_description: The Christ Church Cathedral is a large Gothic-revival cathedral in downtown Victoria, BC. The cathedral has a beautiful stone facade and features a pipe organ and a labyrinth. The cathedral is open for tours every day, and services are held seven days a week, including on Sundays at 8:00 am, 9:15 am, 11:00 am and 4:00 pm.
name: Christ Church Cathedral
address: 930 Burdett Ave, Victoria, BC V8V 3G8, Canada

excerpt: Guided tours of the 36-acre estate & official residence of the lieutenant governor, founded in 1865.
detail_description: Government House, located at 1401 Rockland Avenue in Victoria, British Columbia, is the official residence of the Lieutenant Governors of British Columbia. Established in 1865 and now designated as a National Historic Landmark, it offers guided tours of its 36-acre estate. The house is renowned for its stunning gardens which were initially laid out in 1911 and later redesigned in the 1950s.
name: Government House
address: 1401 Rockland Ave, Victoria, BC V8S 1V9, Canada

excerpt: Visitors can see seals & other marine life along this quaint floating pier with food kiosks & shops.
detail_description: Fisherman's Wharf Park in Victoria, BC, is a delightful waterfront haven that promises an unforgettable experience for visitors of all ages. As you stroll along the charming floating boardwalks, you'll be captivated by the vibrant atmosphere filled with colorful shops and eateries. This unique destination not only showcases picturesque houseboats but also offers a chance to spot playful seals and other marine life basking in their natural habitat.
name: Fisherman's Wharf Park
address: 12 Erie St, Victoria, BC V8V 0B2, Canada

excerpt: Renown harbour ferry, pickle boats & electric vessels offering scenic tours & pub crawls.
detail_description: Victoria Harbour Ferry is a renowned transportation service in Victoria, British Columbia, offering scenic tours and pub crawls on its pickle boats and electric vessels. The ferry provides a delightful experience for kids as it runs passengers to over a dozen locations in the harbor. Additionally, visitors can purchase a longer harbor tour pass for a 45-minute guided journey featuring historic landmarks and breathtaking views of seaplanes taking off and landing.
name: Victoria Harbour Ferry
address: 327 Harbour Rd, Victoria, BC V9A 3S2, Canada

excerpt: Historical objects, art, photos & models showcasing the maritime history of the Pacific Northwest.
detail_description: Located at 744 Douglas Street in Victoria, The Maritime Museum of British Columbia offers a fascinating journey through the maritime history of the Pacific Northwest. Visitors can explore historical objects, art, photos, and models that showcase the region's rich maritime heritage. The museum also hosts engaging programs for children, introducing them to museum learning through themed activities like crafts, play, song, and dance. Additionally, visitors can witness the impressive maneuverability of Victoria Harbour Ferry during the Water Ballet event.
name: The Maritime Museum of British Columbia
address: 744 Douglas St, Victoria, BC V8W 2Z7, Canada

excerpt: Historic site once home of renowned Canadian painter Emily Carr, with gardens & art exhibitions.
detail_description: Nestled in the charming James Bay neighborhood of Victoria, the Carr House National Historic Site is a must-visit for art enthusiasts and history buffs alike. This beautifully restored home, built in 1863, was once the childhood residence of celebrated Canadian painter and author Emily Carr. Visitors can explore her early life through various exhibits showcasing her artwork and literature. The site also features lovely gardens that reflect Victorian-era aesthetics, providing a serene backdrop for reflection.
name: Carr House National Historic Site
address: 207 Government St, Victoria, BC V8V 2K8, Canada

excerpt: Variety of art, including pieces from Canada & Asia, plus gardens with a Japanese Shinto shrine.
detail_description: Immerse yourself in a world of art and nature at the Art Gallery of Greater Victoria. This museum showcases a diverse collection of nearly 20,000 objects from Canada, Asia, and beyond. Explore the historic 1889 Spencer Mansion and seven modern galleries that house an extensive art collection. The gallery also features beautiful gardens with a Japanese Shinto shrine, offering a serene setting to complement the artwork on display.
name: Art Gallery of Greater Victoria
address: 1040 Moss St, Victoria, BC V8V 4P1, Canada

excerpt: Scenic, historic street featuring trendy boutiques,  independent fashion, cafes & accessory shops.
detail_description: Johnson St, also known as LoJo, is a historic and scenic street in Victoria, offering a trendy shopping experience with its boutiques, independent fashion stores, and accessory shops. The area includes Market Square with its unique merchandise and Canada's oldest Chinatown featuring quirky shops and restaurants along Fan Tan Alley. Visitors can explore the candy-colored Victorian-era shopfronts filled with local designers' wares and eco-friendly clothing options.
name: Johnson St
address: Victoria, BC, Canada

excerpt: Installed in 2009, pedestrians are the gnomon for this 18-ft wide, interactive sundial on a pathway.
detail_description: The Ogden Point Sundial, an 18-ft wide interactive sundial, was installed in 2009. It is located near the popular Ogden Point Breakwater in Victoria, British Columbia. The breakwater is an 800-meter walkway that provides relief from the waves and offers stunning views of the harbor and surrounding landscape. Visitors can start their walk at the Ogden Point Cafe on Dallas Road and explore an interpretive exhibit about the breakwater's construction and local marine life.
name: Ogden Point Sundial
address: 211 Dallas Rd, Victoria, BC V8V 1A3, Canada

excerpt: Circa-1872 waterside cemetery with shaded walking paths & historic graves of notable local figures.
detail_description: Ross Bay Cemetery, established in 1873, is a significant historical site in Victoria. It is the resting place of notable local figures such as Sir James Douglas, Robert Dunsmuir, and Emily Carr. The cemetery also holds the graves of nuns from St. Ann's, creating an eerie atmosphere that some believe to be haunted. Despite its spooky reputation, the cemetery's grounds are beautiful and offer a picturesque setting for a leisurely stroll among century-old trees overlooking the ocean shore.
name: Ross Bay Cemetery
address: 1495 Fairfield Rd, Victoria, BC V8S 3L6, Canada

detail_description: Government Street is a bustling thoroughfare that runs through downtown Victoria, offering a delightful mix of shopping and architectural charm. As you stroll along the Inner Harbour, you'll encounter Artinas Jewelry, known for its vast collection of Canadian hand-crafted jewelry. Nearby, Cowichan Trading and Sasquatch Trading Ltd. showcase authentic Indigenous arts, crafts, and moccasins. The street also features an array of unique shops selling native art, jewelry, clothing, toys, and more.
name: Government St
address: Victoria, BC, Canada

detail_description: Beacon Hill Children's Farm is a charming addition to a day spent in Beacon Hill Park, offering kids the chance to experience farm life without leaving the city. Located in downtown Victoria, this farm within a city is home to pigs, donkeys, chickens, goats, and peacocks. Visitors can witness the exciting Running of the Goats at 10:10 AM during the summer season. The petting zoo provides an educational and entertaining experience for families while being donation-based.
name: Beacon Hill Children's Farm
address: 815 Circle Dr, Victoria, BC V8V 2P2, Canada

excerpt: Waterfront thoroughfare featuring access to public parks, picturesque overlooks & a cruise terminal.
detail_description: Dallas Road is a scenic waterfront thoroughfare in Victoria, offering access to public parks, picturesque overlooks, and a cruise terminal. The road stretches from Erie St. to Hollywood Crescent, providing ample angled parking for visitors to stop and explore various points of interest along the way. This route takes you past Beacon Hill Park, Clover Point - a popular kite-flying spot, and the Ross Bay Cemetery.
name: Dallas Rd
address: Victoria, BC, Canada

excerpt: Local boutiques & eateries occupy historic brick buildings around a relaxed courtyard with seating.
detail_description: Market Square in Victoria, Canada is a charming historic area with brick buildings housing local boutiques and eateries. The relaxed courtyard offers seating and hosts a Sunday flea market for great deals. This unique shopping area is hidden from view from the street, featuring open-air spaces behind beautifully restored historical buildings. With patios lining the multileveled area and regular performances in the sunny main square, it's a great spot to visit even on rainy days due to its covered sections.
name: Market Square
address: 560 Johnson St #39, Victoria, BC V8W 3C6, Canada

excerpt: Cozy, urban speakeasy providing a chill atmosphere, an imaginative, elevated menu & craft cocktails.
detail_description: Little Jumbo Restaurant and Bar is a cozy urban speakeasy that offers an imaginative menu and craft cocktails. Established in 2013, it was initially hidden from the public, adding to its allure as a difficult-to-find gem in Victoria. The establishment has been at the forefront of cocktail culture, utilizing innovative techniques such as nitrogen-chilled glassware and live smoke infusions.
name: Little Jumbo Restaurant and Bar
address: Down the Hall, 506 Fort St #102, Victoria, BC V8W 1E6, Canada

excerpt: Affluent Oak Bay is popular for its tree-lined namesake avenue, filled with smart boutiques and art galleries, fancy delis, and lively cafes. Casual spots serving brunch and fish and chips buzz with locals in nearby Estevan Village. A short stroll away, Willows Beach has calm waters for kayaking and paddleboarding, while yachts pack Oak Bay Marina. A coastal drive passes the Victoria Golf Club and ritzy Uplands area.
detail_description: Oak Bay is an upscale neighborhood known for its elegant Oak Bay Avenue, featuring chic boutiques, art galleries, and charming cafes. Nearby Estevan Village offers casual dining options popular with locals. Willows Beach provides a tranquil setting for water activities like kayaking and paddleboarding, while Oak Bay Marina attracts yacht enthusiasts. A scenic coastal drive showcases the Victoria Golf Club and the affluent Uplands area.
name: Oak Bay
address: British Columbia, Canada

detail_description: Eagle Wing Whale & Wildlife Tours is a highly acclaimed and reputable company that offers an exceptional whale watching experience. Their comfortable and safe open or closed boats provide the perfect vantage point to spend about three hours observing these magnificent creatures in the waters around Vancouver Island. With a strong focus on sustainability, they offer four different types of boats for travelers to choose from, ensuring a memorable and eco-friendly adventure.
name: Eagle Wing Whale & Wildlife Tours
address: 1 Dallas Rd, Victoria, BC V8V 0B2, Canada

excerpt: Founded by a famous author, this acclaimed store offers a wide variety of books in an elegant space.
detail_description: Munro's Books, located on Government Street in Victoria, is a renowned bookstore founded by a well-known author. The store offers an extensive collection of books in a sophisticated setting and is adorned with eye-catching holiday red bows. It was recognized by National Geographic as one of the world's top 10 bookstores in 2015. The beautifully renovated old building features stunning tapestries and houses a well-organized selection of books, including a dedicated children's section.
name: Munro's Books
address: 1108 Government St, Victoria, BC V8W 1Y2, Canada

detail_description: Fan Tan Alley, located in Victoria's Chinatown, is renowned as the narrowest street in North America. Once a notorious gambling and opium hotspot in the 1800s, it has now transformed into a vibrant alley filled with quirky boutiques and the iconic Gates of Harmonious Interest. Spanning just three feet wide in some sections, this historic landmark offers visitors a unique experience as they stroll through its pedestrian pathway.
name: Fan Tan Alley
address: 2 Fan Tan Alley, Victoria, BC V8W 1R3, Canada

detail_description: Five Star Whale Watching, located in Victoria, is the premier whale watching company affiliated with the renowned Fairmont Empress hotel. Offering four distinct tour options throughout the year, visitors can embark on an Ultimate Marine Adventure Tour, Standard 3-hour Whale Watching Tours, Marine Wildlife Tours, and Sunset & Whales Tours. Certified naturalists guide guests through the waters to witness orcas, gray whales, humpback whales, minke whales and other marine wildlife up close.
name: Five Star Whale Watching
address: 645 Humboldt St, Victoria, BC V8W 1W5, Canada

detail_description: Orca Spirit Adventures Whale Watching offers an unforgettable experience for wildlife enthusiasts. Visitors rave about the knowledgeable and respectful captains who ensure a memorable encounter with orcas, humpback whales, dolphins, sea lions, and seals. The tours are praised for their comfortable amenities such as enclosed cabins with great views, complimentary coffee and tea, and engaging staff who entertain and educate guests throughout the journey.
name: Orca Spirit Adventures Whale Watching
address: 146 Kingston St, Victoria, BC V8V 1V4, Canada

excerpt: Victoria, capital of British Columbia, sits on the craggy southern end of Vancouver Island. With abundant parkland, it’s known for outdoor activities. The city's British colonial past shows in its Victorian architecture, including stately Craigdarroch Castle mansion. Butchart Gardens, with 55 acres of vivid floral displays, plus statuary, water features and a carousel, is one of many formal gardens in the city.
detail_description: Victoria, the capital of British Columbia, is located on the southern end of Vancouver Island and offers abundant parkland for outdoor activities. The city's British colonial history is reflected in its Victorian architecture, such as the impressive Craigdarroch Castle mansion. Visitors can explore attractions like Butchart Gardens with its 55 acres of vibrant floral displays and various formal gardens.
name: Victoria
address: British Columbia, Canada

detail_description: The McPherson Playhouse, also known as The Mac, is a historic theater located in Victoria's Centennial Square complex. Originally opened in 1914 as the Pantages Theatre, it was renamed after Thomas Shanks McPherson and underwent reconstruction in 1965. With its stunning Neo-Baroque style auditorium and modern lobby addition, The Mac is renowned for its excellent acoustics and architectural beauty.
name: McPherson Playhouse
address: 3 Centennial Square, Victoria, BC V8W 1P5, Canada

excerpt: Urban shopping mall since 1989, with brand-name retailers, dining options & underground parking.
detail_description: The Bay Centre, an urban shopping mall established in 1989, is a popular destination in the heart of Victoria's Downtown Shopping district. Boasting over 90 street front and interior stores, it offers a diverse range of brand-name retailers and dining options. The mall's architectural design is both intriguing and conveniently located with underground parking. Welcoming over 7 million guests annually, it spans an entire city block and appeals to visitors exploring downtown Victoria.
name: The Bay Centre
address: 1150 Douglas St, Victoria, BC V8W 3M9, Canada

excerpt: Historic building with local vendors offering gourmet foods, handcrafted goods & live entertainment.
detail_description: Victoria Public Market at the Hudson is a historic downtown market located in the Hudson building in Victoria. It offers a wide range of locally-produced goods, including gourmet foods, handcrafted items, and live entertainment. The market features vendors offering farm-fresh groceries, handmade pies, French bakery products, oils and vinegars, fresh flowers, specialty retail items, and gourmet food services. Additionally, it hosts a day vendor program showcasing Vancouver Island's artisans and makers.
name: Victoria Public Market at the Hudson
address: 1701 Douglas St #6, Victoria, BC V8W 0B8, Canada

excerpt: Quaint establishment featuring a wide selection gourmet chocolates in specialty assortments & tins.
detail_description: Rogers' Chocolates is a historic and charming chocolate shop located on Government Street in Victoria. Established in 1885, it is known as Canada's first chocolatier. The store offers a wide selection of gourmet chocolates in specialty assortments and tins. Visitors can also explore the haunted aspect of the establishment, as it is rumored to be home to the ghosts of Charles and Leah Rogers. The mouth-wateringly good chocolates are favored by many, including the Royal Family.
name: Rogers' Chocolates
address: 913 Government St, Victoria, BC V8W 1X5, Canada

detail_description: Orca Spirit Adventures Whale Watching is a renowned eco-tourism destination located in Port Renfrew, at the junction of the West Coast and Juan de Fuca Trails. The company offers daily departures from various locations within Victoria, on Vancouver Island. Visitors can enjoy 3-hour whale watching tours in open zodiacs or covered boats, with the option to combine the experience with attractions like Butchart Gardens.
name: Orca Spirit Adventures Whale Watching
address: 950 Wharf St, Victoria, BC V8W 1T4, Canada

excerpt: Dockside seafood restaurant known for its creative, hand-roll-style tacos. Open seasonally.
detail_description: Red Fish Blue Fish is a seasonal dockside seafood restaurant in Victoria, BC, known for its creative hand-roll-style tacos and modern take on traditional seafood dishes. The restaurant has gained acclaim and popularity, being featured in media outlets like the Lonely Planet Guide, the Today Show, and Food Network Canada's Eat Street. As an Ocean Wise partner, Red Fish Blue Fish showcases sustainably sourced seafood with a menu that offers a fresh twist on quintessential seafood recipes.
name: Red Fish Blue Fish
address: 1006 Wharf St, Victoria, BC V8W 1N8, Canada

excerpt: Rooms in an 1884 house, casual suites & a bungalow joined to a craft brewery with free breakfast.
detail_description: Spinnakers Gastro Brewpub & GuestHouses is a historic destination that has been serving craft beer and fine dining since 1984. It is Canada's oldest brewpub, offering a diverse range of house-brewed beers, including innovative ales and classic styles. The menu features delicious dishes made from locally sourced ingredients that pair perfectly with their brews. Guests can enjoy the picturesque ocean-front setting, heated waterfront patio, and spacious guest houses for an immersive experience.
name: Spinnakers Gastro Brewpub & GuestHouses
address: 308 Catherine St, Victoria, BC V9A 3S8, Canada

detail_description: Parliament House is a stunning attraction best visited in the morning to capture its beauty in natural light. The iconic building is set against a backdrop of lush greenery and the ocean, making it perfect for photography. Whether you're into history, architecture, or seeking a peaceful retreat with breathtaking views, Parliament House is not to be missed. The surrounding area exudes charm with its picturesque parks, fountains, statues, and colorful flowers that transport visitors back in time.
name: Parliament House
address: Government St, Victoria, BC V8V 2H2, Canada

excerpt: Elegant rooms & suites in a polished, Victorian B&B offering a genteel tearoom with harbour views.
detail_description: The Pendray Inn and Tea House, located in Victoria's Inner Harbour, offers an elegant Victorian B&B experience with a charming tearoom that provides picturesque views of the harbor. This historic establishment beautifully combines British tea traditions with a touch of West Coast influence. Situated conveniently near popular attractions like Fisherman's Wharf and the seaplane terminal, it serves as an ideal stop for both travelers and locals seeking a refined experience.
name: Pendray Inn
address: 309 Belleville St., Victoria, BC V8V 1X2, Canada

excerpt: This restaurant & cafe serves simple farm-fresh mains & snacks in an airy, bright Victorian house.
detail_description: Nourish Kitchen & Cafe is a charming restaurant and cafe located in an 1889 heritage home in Victoria's James Bay neighborhood. The cozy eatery offers a seasonal menu with farm-fresh mains and snacks, catering to vegans, vegetarians, and health-conscious diners. The philosophy of the mother-daughter duo owners revolves around creating delicious dishes using locally sourced ingredients that are good for the body.
name: Nourish Kitchen & Cafe
address: 225 Quebec St, Victoria, BC V8V 1W2, Canada

detail_description: Embark on a delightful culinary adventure with A Taste of Victoria Food Tours, led by the knowledgeable guide and founder, Andy. The two-hour tour takes you through the Victoria Public Food Market to sample pierogies, Queen Elizabeth-approved chocolates, and porchetta-topped meatballs. You'll also explore Fan Tan Alley and visit local breweries to experience the city's craft beer scene. This immersive experience covers about 2.5 km including Chinatown, Old Town, and the Inner Harbour.
name: A Taste of Victoria Food Tours
address: Inside Phillips Brewery Tasting Room, 2000 Government St, Victoria, BC V8T 4P1, Canada

excerpt: Well-known viewpoint from a former weather station offering scenic ocean & city views.
detail_description: The observatory, open since 1925, offers scenic ocean and city views from its perch atop Gonzales Hill. In the evening, make the quick walk up to the top for a breathtaking view. Warning: construction is taking place in the area, so be aware of blast horns and explosions afterwards.
name: Gonzales Observatory
address: 302 Denison Rd, Victoria, BC V8S 4K3, Canada

excerpt: Modern Pacific Northwest restaurant for dry-aged steak & seafood, plus a raw bar, cocktails & a wine program.
detail_description: The Courtney Room is a stylish and elegant restaurant located inside the Magnolia Hotel & Spa. Since its opening in 2018, it has garnered numerous accolades for its classic French techniques combined with fresh local ingredients. The menu features dry-aged steak, seafood, a raw bar, and mouthwatering dishes like the duck-fat cooked tater tots with pickled shallot-ranch dipping sauce.
name: The Courtney Room
address: 623 Courtney St, Victoria, BC V8W 1B8, Canada

detail_description: The Inner Harbour Causeway in Victoria, BC, is a charming waterfront area that runs beneath the parliament buildings and the Empress Hotel. Once a commercial port, it has transformed into a popular tourist spot with plaques and monuments along its walls. The causeway offers picturesque views of boats and historic buildings, creating an enchanting ambiance day or night. Visitors can explore shops, restaurants, and attractions while enjoying street performers and watching boats pass by.
name: Inner Harbour Causeway
address: 790 Government St, Victoria, BC V8W 3M6, Canada

detail_description: Cook St is a vibrant and diverse street known for its eclectic mix of restaurants, cafes, and shops. It's a food lover's paradise with a wide range of international cuisines to choose from, including Italian, Japanese, and Mexican. The street has a lively atmosphere with colorful storefronts and bustling sidewalks, making it perfect for leisurely strolls and people-watching. In addition to dining options, Cook St also offers unique shopping experiences with boutique stores selling everything from fashion to home decor.
name: Cook St
address: Capital Regional District, BC, Canada

detail_description: Embark on a leisurely Tally-Ho Carriage tour through Beacon Hill Park for a delightful introduction to island living. This historic carriage business in Victoria offers flexible scheduling, accommodating early tours and even allowing for an extended exploration of the area. The experienced guide provides fascinating insights into local culture and points out interesting details along the way, making the ride both informative and enjoyable.
name: Tally-Ho Carriage Tours
address: 465 Belleville St., Victoria, BC V8V 2L8, Canada
